  "prompt": "What is the meaning of the phrase - 'majboori ka naam mahatma gandhi'?",
  "response": "The phrase \"majboori ka naam Mahatma Gandhi\" is a popular saying in India. It can be translated to \"compulsion is named Mahatma Gandhi\" or \"helplessness is called Mahatma Gandhi.\" This phrase is often used in a sarcastic or humorous context to refer to situations where people feel compelled or forced to do something against their will or when they have no choice but to go along with something reluctantly.\n\nThe phrase reflects how the name of Mahatma Gandhi, a revered figure associated with principles of non-violence, freedom, and determination, is ironically invoked in situations of helplessness or compulsion. It\u2019s a way to highlight the contrast between Gandhi\u2019s ideals and the reality of feeling compelled or constrained by circumstances.\n\nKeep in mind that this phrase is often used colloquially and may have different connotations depending on the context in which it is used.",
